{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637164"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:38:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:38:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17634"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17634"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10348"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71805"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10348"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17634"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57294"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10008"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24201"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24206"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24237"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71805"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPepsin is a crucial digestive enzyme produced by chief cells in the gastric mucosa.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the optimal pH for pepsin activity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["pH 8.5","pH 7.4","pH 6.0","pH 4.5","pH 2.0"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPepsin functions optimally at \u003Cstrong\u003EpH 2.0\u003C/strong\u003E. This acidic environment is maintained by gastric parietal cells which secrete hydrochloric acid. The low pH is essential not only for optimal enzyme activity but also for the conversion of pepsinogen to active pepsin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 4.5\u003C/strong\u003E - While pepsin retains some activity at this pH, it is significantly reduced compared to pH 2.0\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 6.0\u003C/strong\u003E - Pepsin has minimal activity at this pH and pepsinogen activation is inhibited\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 7.4\u003C/strong\u003E - Pepsin begins to denature at neutral pH\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EpH 8.5\u003C/strong\u003E - Pepsin is completely and irreversibly denatured in alkaline conditions\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen gastric contents enter the duodenum, the alkaline environment (pH \u0026gt;7.0) inactivates pepsin, preventing damage to the intestinal mucosa. This demonstrates the importance of pH in regulating digestive enzyme activity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pepsin is secreted as inactive pepsinogen and requires an acidic environment (pH \u003C3.5) for activation.","Pepsin functions optimally at pH 2.0 and becomes irreversibly denatured above pH 7.0.","Pepsin is the primary enzyme responsible for protein digestion in the stomach."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57294"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17634"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57294"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T16:01:00+10:30","updated